## When to use this pattern

Avoid asking users for gender and always follow the
[guidelines on the GOV.UK Design System](https://design-system.service.gov.uk/patterns/gender-or-sex/).

Use this pattern when you need to provide a gender for a user to an external
system, where that gender is constrained to a binary response. For example, if
HMRC require a 'female' or 'male' value to identify an individual for payroll.

This is a very specific scenario, however the research and design decisions that
went into creating this pattern may be insightful for other teams.

## When not to use this pattern

Do not use this pattern to ask users how they identify their gender.

## How it works

In our example, we needed to provide HMRC with a value for gender.

HMRC currently only recognise Male and Female genders as a method of identifying
a user's tax accounts (along with other identifiers).

Gender is a required field.

We designed this pattern to avoid asking the user for their gender when we only
needed to know what HMRC were most likely to have recorded, in order to match a
user to that record.

To remain sympathetic to users, and transparent about why we're asking for this
information:

- tell users exactly what information you're asking for
- explain why you're asking for this information
- let users know what you'll do with their data
- provide an option for those who do not know (this is different to providing an
"I prefer not to say" option)
- let users know what you'll do if they cannot provide this information
- do not store this information if you do not need to do so

